<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution and remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This is a predominantly central and northern European bee, but there are isolated southern populations in upland areas of Spain, Portugal, and Turkey (
<bibRefCitation author="Gusenleitner, F" journalOrPublisher="Entomofauna Supplement" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 1280" refId="B15" refString="Gusenleitner, F, Schwarz, M, 2002. Weltweite Checkliste der Bienengattung Andrena mit Bemerkungen und Ergaenzungen zu palaearktischen Arten (Hymenoptera, Apidae, Andreninae, Andrena). Entomofauna Supplement 10: 1 - 1280" title="Weltweite Checkliste der Bienengattung Andrena mit Bemerkungen und Ergaenzungen zu palaearktischen Arten (Hymenoptera, Apidae, Andreninae, Andrena)." volume="10" year="2002">Gusenleitner and Schwarz 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4790.2.1" author="Wood, TJ" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="201 - 228" refId="B61" refString="Wood, TJ, Cross, I, Baldock, DW, 2020a. Updates to the bee fauna of Portugal with the description of three new Iberian Andrena species (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Anthophila). Zootaxa 4790: 201 - 228, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4790.2.1" title="Updates to the bee fauna of Portugal with the description of three new Iberian Andrena species (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Anthophila)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4790.2.1" volume="4790" year="2020 a">Wood et al. 2020a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena synadelpha" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="synadelpha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena synadelpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is polylectic, but it prefers pollen from trees and shrubs of broadleaf woodland such as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acer" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Acer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rubus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Rubus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rhamnaceae" genus="Rhamnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rhamnus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Rhamnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rhamnaceae" genus="Frangula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Frangula" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Frangula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="Ilex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ilex" order="Aquifoliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ilex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biocon.2017.09.009" author="Wood, TJ" journalOrPublisher="Biological Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="72 - 80" refId="B58" refString="Wood, TJ, Roberts, SPM, 2017. An assessment of historical and contemporary diet breadth in polylectic Andrena bee species. Biological Conservation 215: 72 - 80, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biocon.2017.09.009" title="An assessment of historical and contemporary diet breadth in polylectic Andrena bee species." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biocon.2017.09.009" volume="215" year="2017">Wood and Roberts 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Its presence in the Middle Atlas is therefore unexpected, but it has precedence. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena haemorrhoa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haemorrhoa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena haemorrhoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fabricius, 1781), another predominantly central and northern European bee which is able to live as far north as the Arctic circle, was also recently found in the Ouled Nail mountains of Algeria at an elevation of 761 meters (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4001/003.021.0224" author="Cherair, EH" journalOrPublisher="African Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="287 - 293" refId="B7" refString="Cherair, EH, Scheuchl, E, Doumandji, S, Louadi, K, 2013. A new record and a new subspecies of Andrena haemorrhoa (Fabricius, 1781). African Entomology 21: 287 - 293, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4001/003.021.0224" title="A new record and a new subspecies of Andrena haemorrhoa (Fabricius, 1781)." url="https://doi.org/10.4001/003.021.0224" volume="21" year="2013">Cherair et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). It remains to be seen if there are more typically 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘European’">'European'</normalizedToken>
<taxonomicName authorityName="tenebricorpus Wood" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="incertae sedis" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species that persist in the mountains of North Africa, presumably having been isolated at the end of the Ice Age as the lowland areas of North Africa returned to a more arid climate.
</paragraph>
